				<div class="postbody">
				Aeolion, the halogens emitted by volcanos tend to be in elemental form. Such as bromine or chlorine molecules. Those chemically react in the stratosphere to form things like HCl (called hydrochloric acid, when dissolved in water), a water soluble molecule which then falls out in (acidic) rain. Chlorofluorocarbons (like freon) are very chemically stable (which is why they are used as refrigerants). They rise in the atmosphere without chemically reacting at all. It is only in the upper atmosphere where UV radiation is so strong that it can break up some molecules where CFCs break down. Halogen ions form a catalytic reaction with ozone to break the ozone down into oxygen molecules. Research has shown that a single halogen atom will break down thousands to millions of ozone molecules before reacting with something more stable (like hydrogen) and getting removed from the cycle. And yes, ozone is helpful when it is several miles up in the atmosphere, and harmful pollution when it is near ground level.
<br />

<br />
The point is, that halogens emitted from volcanos, and other natural sources doesn't get to the ozone layer to cause problems. CFCs do. 
<br />

<br />
Poppa, the consensus of peer-reviewed scientific literature is that global warming exists, and it is a problem to worry about. Unscientific articles claim that there is no problem. I'm not going to deny that there is a lot of pop-ecology going on: that group subscribes to either cases 1 or 4 of the cases I pointed out on page 1 of this thread. <span style="font-style: italic">Dilution is the solution</span> was the slogan in the 50s and 60s of the pollutionist version of pop-ecology. 
<br />

<br />
The orbit of the earth is not perfectly circular. It is eliptical. When the northern hemisphere is in winter-mode, the earth is actually closer to the sun than during the northern summer-mode. Which means that a southern summer will have stronger light (and more UV) than a northern summer. Satellite sensors show high levels of CFCs in and around the ozone hole over the antarctic.<br />
